Part I – Foundations 

Introduction 

Purpose of the Textbook 

Climbing is hard. Routesetting is harder. Ask any setter about their upbringing in the craft, and you will likely hear some form of lackluster mentorship and guidance. Because of the infinite complexities of climbing and the nature of our job, the learning process can quickly become convoluted, niche, and frustrating.  

Our goal is to make this learning process clear and progressive. Routesetting often feels overwhelming because it demands mastery of climbing movement, design theory, and hardware skills all while relying on physical wellbeing, safety protocols, and community engagement. By breaking these masteries down into sections, this textbook helps new setters develop autonomy and strive for progression through the many avenues of setting.  

It is very important to remember that this is not a rigid rulebook. There is no “right” way to set climbs, and everyone approaches it differently. Instead, we wanted to create a living document to reference as you grow. We always encourage experimentation, iteration, and a bit of breaking the rules.  

 
How to Use This Guide 

This textbook is broken down into 5 Parts: Foundations, Apprenticeship Framework, Key Concepts, Deep Dives, and the Appendix. In each Part are subsections that provide easy navigation and a more narrow scope than the broader section. 

Foundations covers the very basics and is mostly a reference for Day 1 on the job.  

Apprenticeship Framework is the meat and potatoes for mentors and apprentices alike. It offers a phase-based approach for bringing an F1 or F2 level apprentice into a self-sufficient F3 capable routesetter. We believe that meaningful progression through these phases means you are ready for a career, local travel, and potentially full-time status. 

Key Concepts are deeper dives into important ideas behind our job. In it you will find mostly abstract writings about what and why, but not necessarily how. Keep in mind that these are opinions based on the experience of various setters, not objective truths. 

The Appendix is not to be confused with the human appendix. 

 

 
Routesetting Philosophy 

Maybe a couple small paragraphs on the broad “why”, fun, sustainability and such 

Routesetters frequently lose the forest for the trees; and they’ll be the first to admit it. Behind all the theory and experimentation is the simple fact that we screw plastic to a wall for a living and people find joy in that space. That joy is paramount. Without it we have no members, no money, and no job. Back to the office we go! 

At the end of the day, people doing climbs is good. We will worry about unforced sequences, downgrades, upgrades, tall beta, craftsmanship, design theory, color theory, and how much our elbows and fingers and everything else hurt. But it is often the case that the climber getting to the top of the climb is a net positive. What joy! 

But with all this comes the aforementioned labor toll. Our bodies can only handle so much and everybody handles the same things very differently. While pushing our craft and getting the work done is important, it is even more important that we keep our bodies healthy.  

