I see two ways through this, obviously dependent on the exact apprentice and their style: 

Approach A: Quality (Luke’s idea) 

“Slow is smooth, smooth is fast.” 

Phase 1: Set 2-3 boulders per day, avoiding ropes for now. Focus on commercial flow, forcing sequences, and comfort.  

Phase 2: The base quality is there, now do it more efficiently. Learn the ropes (literally) up to 1 route/day.  

Only worry about boulders for an arbitrary amount of time. Then introduce WAH. 

Approach B: Pace (Nicole’s idea) 

“You can’t refine a product you didn’t finish.” 

Phase 1: Get up to pace setting 4 boulders and up to 2 routes. Do it safely while gaining autonomy and understanding along the way. 

Phase 2: Now that you can get the product on the wall, slow down and refine skill. 

Ropes along the way the whole time. 

Approach A: Quality (Luke’s Idea) 

Luke’s proposition: 3 phases, boulder-oriented at the start, ropes later. 

Phase 1: Fundamentals & Flow 

    Focus: Understanding movement, tool competence, and the "Why." 

    Volume: Low | 2-3 Boulders per day 

    Ropes: None. 

    Why? Cognitive load. Learning to create good movement is mentally exhausting. Learning to not die on a rope is mentally exhausting. Doing both at the same time results in bad setting and safety mistakes (ask me how I know). Let them master the drill on a ladder first. 

    Exit Criteria (loose and always open for discussion):  

    Set 4 boulders in a day for the first time. 

    Fulfilled some commercial flow and basic comp move assignments. 

Phase 2: Efficiency & Verticality 

    Focus: Now we add time pressure. Introduce Ropesetting (WAH) and demand efficiency (to an extent of course. We all have those days). 

    Volume: Standard (Matching typical crew pace of 3-4+ boulders, 1-1.5+ routes). 

    Ropes (WAH): INTRODUCED. 

    This could be Month 2 or Month 3. The trigger isn't a given time but is more like mastery of Phase 1. Once they can set decent boulders without thinking too hard, they have the brain space to learn WAH. 

    Exit Criteria:  

    Stripped and set a zone at the usual crew pace. Basic WAH proficiency. 

    Used all extraneous tools at least once: ratchet, vice grips, bolt cutter, etc. 

Phase 3: Style & Autonomy 

    Focus: Aesthetics, more complex assignments, and volume utility. 

    Volume: Typical F3 quota.  

    Exit Criteria:  

    Explored setting at/beyond their project limit. 

    Explored various aesthetic and movement styles. 

    Led placement for a big volume day in the morning. 

    Tagged the set for a day (alongside head/lead setter). 

Exit Criteria and phase progression at the discretion of both the entire crew and apprentice, encouraging open dialogue and “we’re all doing this to different extents every day.” Progress is rarely linear. Encourage overlap between phases, allowing apprentices to advance in areas where they excel while continuing to refine their skills in others. 

