Part III – Key Concepts 

Feedback Loops 

Arguably, the most important single trait for refining your sets is developing an internal feedback loop. In forerunning, and especially when reviewing assignment climbs, we discuss what works and what doesn’t work. We ask questions not only to clarify, but to verbalize a climber’s in-the-moment feeling and mesh that with the intended nature of the climb.  

We often arrive at solutions by asking questions that highlight a problem. Why do I want to cross instead of match? Why does the pogo not feel right? What allows me to gain this position first instead of doing the sequence I want? These come up in daily discussions during forerunning, but we must also keep them in our head when setting. Thus arises the need for a self-critical feedback loop.  

Asking yourself questions as you set is critical; it saves time, it develops intuition, it makes forerunning easier, and it encourages a constant self-critique in search of betterment. A simple question you can ask yourself for almost any climb is “What can the climber do that isn’t what I want?” And then, of course, “why?”.  The “what” is easy. The “why” ... not so much. 

Let’s run through a simple example. You are setting a V3 focused on a critical heel hook. Perhaps you’re aiming to develop a moderate climbers’ ability to intuit heel-hooking and develop that skill at an approachable level. With that goal in mind you put some holds on the wall and get the sequence going. And so you begin: “What can the climber do that isn’t a heel hook?” You first recognize that the climber may decide to skip the heel hook entirely. Okay, you ask yourself, “why?” Are the given feet too secure? Is the position not off-balance enough? Are the holds too downpulling? Is the heel too high? Too low? Does the climber get enough opposition with the heel hook? Does the heel hook allow the climber to gain a hold/position that otherwise would be too difficult to gain? Is it V3 to do the heel hook or V6? Is it V4 to skip the heel hook or V2? Is the heel comfortable enough to be intuitive? How much hip mobility does it require? Is it hard on the knees?  

Out of all the possible answers of that jumble of questions, there's some method that's the easiest way forward. Like all things in climbing, the answer is contextual to several factors such as grade, wall angle, hold choice, intended audience, and much more. As you run through these questions for setting a heel hook, you’ll notice patterns of answers that are generally true that make heel hooking feel good. The more heel hooks you set, the more questions you ask, answer, and iterate on. This is the fundamental feedback loop of routesetting. 

We can generalize this process and apply it to any climb we set. The only requirement is that we have a desired outcome beforehand. In the previous example, the desired outcome was helping “a moderate climber to intuit heel-hooking and develop that skill at an approachable level.” If you have your goal in mind, your questions at the ready, and are prepared to iterate over and over and over again, you will become a better routesetter.   

