Aesthetics 

Like all things in climbing, aesthetics are incredibly subjective. The purpose of this section is not to box you in to the pre-existing design philosophy of one setter/crew/region, but to use their existing experience as a starting point for developing your own aesthetic voice.  

You have a vocabulary of movement from Commercial Flow and Coordination Moves. Aesthetics is about learning how to arrange those movements into compelling experiences on the wall. Can we create a climb that not only feels good to move on but also invites the climber to try from across the gym? What sparks that invitation? 

A newer setter will struggle to balance this mix of form and function, having to make concessions one way or another. A good setter incorporates aesthetics as a typical part of their work; integrating their climbs within the broader context of the set/gym and striving towards a cohesive visual feel. A great setter does the above with no second thought, as it is an intuitive part of their creative process. They push the boundaries of design space in routesetting while maintaining functionality, assignment accuracy, and safety. 

 

